P.body:
This question will resolve as Yes if, by December 31, 2024, there is significant evidence that the development of technology has had a major influence on the outcome of the 2024 US presidential election. Significant influence includes, but is not limited to:
- The use of artificial intelligence in campaign strategies or voter engagement that demonstrably shifts voter preferences or turnout;
- Documented instances of cybersecurity breaches or electronic voting interference that impact the election's integrity or outcome;
- The deployment of new technology platforms or tools that play a pivotal role in shaping public opinion or election results.

Evidence must come from credible sources, such as official government reports, verified data from reputable cybersecurity firms, or coverage by at least three major news organizations (e.g., BBC, The New York Times, The Washington Post). In the absence of direct evidence, a consensus among political analysts or scholars, supported by empirical data, may also be considered.

In the event of ambiguous outcomes, the question will resolve based on the preponderance of credible evidence available by the resolution date.

para_P.body:
This question will be answered with Yes if, by December 31, 2024, there is substantial proof that technological advancements have significantly impacted the result of the 2024 US presidential election. Significant impact includes, but is not limited to:
- The application of artificial intelligence in campaign strategies or voter engagement that noticeably alters voter preferences or turnout;
- Verified cases of cybersecurity breaches or tampering with electronic voting that affect the election's integrity or result;
- The introduction of new technological platforms or tools that are instrumental in shaping public opinion or election outcomes.

Proof must be sourced from credible entities, such as official government reports, verified data from reputable cybersecurity firms, or reports by at least three major news organizations (e.g., BBC, The New York Times, The Washington Post). In the absence of direct proof, a consensus among political analysts or scholars, backed by empirical data, may also be considered.

In the case of unclear outcomes, the question will be resolved based on the preponderance of credible evidence available by the resolution date.

